Both output files are written and the transcript validates cleanly against `transcript_schema.json`.

**What I did across 25 iterations:**

- **Iter 1:** Treatment main effects on ORR. Only pembrolizumab significant (+1 pp).
- **Iter 2–3, 24:** Pembrolizumab × PD-L1 and × TMB-high — both strong positive interactions; combined PDL1≥0.5 + TMB-high stratum gives +13.9 pp absolute ORR boost.
- **Iter 4–6:** Matched targeted-therapy × biomarker (osimertinib×EGFR, sotorasib×KRAS_G12C, olaparib×BRCA2) — **all null** in this cohort.
- **Iter 7–8:** Pembrolizumab × STK11 (significantly negative; survives adjustment), × KEAP1 (null).
- **Iter 9–13, 25:** Prognostic clinico-lab variables — ECOG, albumin, CRP, weight loss, brain mets, stage IV all strongly significant in expected directions; LDH, NLR, liver/bone mets null.
- **Iter 14–18, 20–22:** Smoking/histology/age/TP53/ALK/insurance/rural null; sex_female positive (main effect and pembrolizumab interaction); race marginal.
- **Iter 19:** SNP scan — 0/23 significant after Bonferroni.
- **Iter 23, 25:** Multivariable adjusted model confirming pembro×PDL1, pembro×TMB, pembro×STK11 and the prognostic covariates; refuting the targeted-therapy interactions.

The dataset's clearest signal is the pembrolizumab biomarker triad (PD-L1+, TMB+, STK11−) plus classical prognostics (ECOG, albumin, CRP, weight loss, brain mets, stage IV); the targeted-therapy effects expected from the clinical literature were not present.
